<p>Where generic alternatives exist, NHS purchasing of branded drugs has a number of effects:</p>
<p style="padding-left: 30px;">1. With a finite amount of money to spend on treatments, giving a patient an expensive drug where cheaper equivalents with the same effect exist means that other patients can’t have the care that they need.</p>
<p style="padding-left: 30px;">2. Newer more expensive drugs can expose patients to unnecessary risk since they have generally been tried and tested by fewer people.</p>
<p style="padding-left: 30px;">3. Rewarding the drug industry for poor investments by spending millions on a drug that produces at best a small incremental change creates a disincentive for risk taking and genuine innovation.</p>
<p>We aim to help the NHS to find opportunities at this time of great change and financial pressure, by clearly identifying and mapping prescribing variation against NICE guidance <a  href="#note2">(2)</a>, using open data. Prescribing variation is a complex picture, but big differences usually suggest an opportunity to save.</p>
<p>This map shows an example: variation in GPs&apos; prescriptions of statins, which are used to lower cholesterol. Annually, this represents over &pound;200 million pounds worth of missed potential savings.</p>



